""content"": ""
    ""Zoekt, en gij zult spinazie eten"" - Jan Eertink

    (""seek, and ye shall eat spinach"" - My primary school teacher)

This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce ""zooked"" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index \
        -name gfiber \
        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ \
        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git \
        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get \
        --url ""http://localhost:6070/search"" \
        --data-urlencode ""q=ngram f:READ"" \
        --data-urlencode ""num=50"" \
        --data-urlencode ""format=json""

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{""GithubUser"": ""username""},
     {""GithubOrg"": ""org""},
     {""GitilesURL"": ""https://gerrit.googlesource.com"", ""Name"": ""zoekt"" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

It is recommended to install [Universal
ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.


# ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS

Thanks to Han-Wen Nienhuys for creating Zoekt. Thanks to Alexander Neubeck for
coming up with this idea, and helping Han-Wen Nienhuys flesh it out.


# FORK DETAILS

Originally this fork contained some changes that do not make sense to upstream
and or have not yet been upstreamed. However, this is now the defacto source
for Zoekt. This section will remain for historical reasons and contains
outdated information. It can be removed once the dust settles on moving from
google/zoekt to sourcegraph/zoekt. Differences:

- [zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver](cmd/zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver/main.go)
  is a Sourcegraph specific command which indexes all enabled repositories on
  Sourcegraph, as well as keeping the indexes up to date.
- We have exposed the API via
  [keegancsmith/rpc](https://github.com/keegancsmith/rpc) (a fork of `net/rpc`
  which supports cancellation).
- Query primitive `BranchesRepos` to efficiently specify a set of repositories to
  search.
- Allow empty shard directories on startup. Needed when starting a fresh
  instance which hasn't indexed anything yet.
- We can return symbol/ctag data in results. Additionally we can run symbol regex queries.
- We search shards in order of repo name and ignore shard ranking.
- Other minor changes.

Assuming you have the gerrit upstream configured, a useful way to see what we
changed is:

``` shellsession
$ git diff gerrit/master -- ':(exclude)vendor/' ':(exclude)Gopkg*'
```

# DISCLAIMER

This is not an official Google product
""

yaml,chat,claude-3-sonnet,chat,question_004/question.yaml,1f757a6675cafa91ba2c09324f6ad57170e54291,,,,0,0,0,0,,,,,,,,,,,"In Go, slices are a fundamental data type that provide a flexible and efficient way to work with sequences of elements. They are built on top of arrays and provide a way to access and manipulate a subset of an array's elements.
Here's how slices work in Go:

- You can create a slice using the built-in `make` function: `slice := make([]type, length, capacity)`. The `length` parameter specifies the initial length of the slice, and the `capacity` parameter specifies the underlying array's capacity.
- You can also create a slice by slicing an array: `array := [5]int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}` and `slice := array[1:4]` (creates a slice with elements at indices 1, 2, and 3).
- You can access individual elements of a slice using the index notation: `slice[index]`.
- Slices are zero-indexed, meaning the first element is at index 0.
- You can modify elements of a slice by assigning new values to the corresponding indices: `slice[2] = 42`.
- The length of a slice is the number of elements it contains, and you can get it using the built-in `len` function: `length := len(slice)`.
- The capacity of a slice is the number of elements in the underlying array, starting from the first element in the slice. You can get it using the built-in `cap` function: `capacity := cap(slice)`.
- When you create a slice from an array or another slice, the capacity is set to the maximum elements available in the underlying array, counting from the start of the new slice.
- You can append elements to a slice using the built-in `append` function: `slice = append(slice, 42, 43)`.
- If the underlying array doesn't have enough capacity to accommodate the new elements, a new array is allocated with a larger capacity, and the existing elements are copied over.
- You can create a new slice by slicing an existing slice: `newSlice := slice[2:4]` (creates a new slice with elements at indices 2 and 3 from the original slice).
- Slicing doesn't copy the underlying array
column2: it creates a new slice that shares the same underlying array as the original slice.

column1: - A nil slice has a length and capacity of 0 and has no underlying array.
- You can check if a slice is nil using the comparison operator: `if slice == nil { ... }`.
- The `slices` package in the Go standard library provides utility functions for working with slices, such as `slices.Contains`, `slices.Sort`, `slices.Index`, and more.

Slices in Go are powerful and efficient because they provide a way to work with arrays without the need for explicit memory management or resizing. They automatically grow as needed and allow for easy manipulation of sequences of elements.",how do slices work in go?,"[

- On Ubuntu/Debian: `sudo apt update && sudo apt install python3.x` (replace `x` with the desired version)
- On CentOS/RHEL: `sudo yum install python3x` (replace `x` with the desired version)
- On macOS (with Homebrew): `brew install python@3.x` (replace `x` with the desired version)
- Download the latest Python installer from https://www.python.org/downloads/
- Run the installer and follow the prompts to install the new version
- **pyenv** (Linux/macOS/Windows): Install pyenv, then use `pyenv install 3.x.y` to install a specific Python version and `pyenv global 3.x.y` to set it as the global version.

- **conda** (cross-platform): Install Anaconda or Miniconda, create a new environment with the desired Python version using `conda create -n myenv python=3.x`, and activate it with `conda activate myenv`.
- On Ubuntu/Debian: `sudo add-apt-repository ppa:deadsnakes/ppa` then `sudo apt install python3.x`
- On CentOS/RHEL: Enable the appropriate repository (e.g., `sudo yum install centos-release-scl`), then install the desired Python version (e.g., `sudo yum install rh-python38`).
After upgrading, you can verify the installed Python version by running `python3 --version` or `python --version` in your terminal or command prompt.
Note: It's generally recommended to use virtual environments to manage different Python versions for different projects to avoid conflicts.",how to upgrade my python version?,"[

It does the following:
1. On initialization, it scans the directory and loads any new or updated `.zoekt` files using the provided `shardLoader`. It also drops (unloads) any `.zoekt` files that have been deleted.
2. It then starts watching the directory using the `fsnotify` package. Whenever a file change event is detected, it rescans the directory and updates the loaded shards accordingly.
3. The `DirectoryWatcher` has a `ready` channel that is closed once the initial scan and watch setup is complete. Callers can use `WaitUntilReady` to block until the watcher is ready.
4. The `Stop` method can be called to stop the directory watcher. It closes the `quit` channel, which signals the watcher goroutine to stop and clean up resources.

The `DirectoryWatcher` is likely used in the Zoekt search engine to watch for changes to the search index shards (the `.zoekt` files) and keep the loaded index up-to-date without having to restart the entire process.",What does directory watcher do?,"[

This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce ""zooked"" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index \
        -name gfiber \
        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ \
        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git \
        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get \
        --url ""http://localhost:6070/search"" \
        --data-urlencode ""q=ngram f:READ"" \
        --data-urlencode ""num=50"" \
        --data-urlencode ""format=json""

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{""GithubUser"": ""username""},
     {""GithubOrg"": ""org""},
     {""GitilesURL"": ""https://gerrit.googlesource.com"", ""Name"": ""zoekt"" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.

""content"": ""
    ""Zoekt, en gij zult spinazie eten"" - Jan Eertink

    (""seek, and ye shall eat spinach"" - My primary school teacher)

This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce ""zooked"" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index \
        -name gfiber \
        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ \
        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git \
        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get \
        --url ""http://localhost:6070/search"" \
        --data-urlencode ""q=ngram f:READ"" \
        --data-urlencode ""num=50"" \
        --data-urlencode ""format=json""

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{""GithubUser"": ""username""},
     {""GithubOrg"": ""org""},
     {""GitilesURL"": ""https://gerrit.googlesource.com"", ""Name"": ""zoekt"" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

It is recommended to install [Universal
ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.


# ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS

Thanks to Han-Wen Nienhuys for creating Zoekt. Thanks to Alexander Neubeck for
coming up with this idea, and helping Han-Wen Nienhuys flesh it out.

google/zoekt to sourcegraph/zoekt. Differences:

- [zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver](cmd/zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver/main.go)
  is a Sourcegraph specific command which indexes all enabled repositories on
  Sourcegraph, as well as keeping the indexes up to date.
- We have exposed the API via
  [keegancsmith/rpc](https://github.com/keegancsmith/rpc) (a fork of `net/rpc`
  which supports cancellation).
- Query primitive `BranchesRepos` to efficiently specify a set of repositories to
  search.
- Allow empty shard directories on startup. Needed when starting a fresh
  instance which hasn't indexed anything yet.
- We can return symbol/ctag data in results. Additionally we can run symbol regex queries.
- We search shards in order of repo name and ignore shard ranking.
- Other minor changes.

Assuming you have the gerrit upstream configured, a useful way to see what we
changed is:

``` shellsession
$ git diff gerrit/master -- ':(exclude)vendor/' ':(exclude)Gopkg*'
```

yaml,chat,claude-3-sonnet,chat,question_021/question.yaml,1f757a6675cafa91ba2c09324f6ad57170e54291,,,,0,0,0,0,,,,,,,,,,,"Goroutines are lightweight threads of execution in Go that are managed by the Go runtime. They work by leveraging the concept of concurrent programming, which allows multiple tasks to make progress simultaneously. Here's a high-level overview of how goroutines work:
1. **Creation**: Goroutines are created by calling the `go` keyword followed by a function call. This function call is executed concurrently with the current goroutine. For example:
go doSomeWork() // creates a new goroutine

2. **Scheduling**: The Go runtime manages the scheduling of goroutines onto the available logical processors (or threads). It uses a technique called ""work stealing"" to efficiently distribute the workload across available processors.

3. **Context Switching**: When a goroutine is blocked (e.g., waiting for I/O or a channel operation), the Go runtime can switch to another goroutine, allowing other goroutines to make progress. This context switching is lightweight and efficient compared to traditional thread context switching.

4. **Communication**: Goroutines communicate via channels, which are typed conduits through which values can be sent and received. Channels provide synchronization and data exchange between goroutines, allowing them to coordinate their work.
5. **Synchronization**: Go provides various synchronization primitives, such as channels, mutexes, and wait groups, to coordinate the execution of goroutines and manage shared resources safely.

6. **Memory Management**: Goroutines share the same address space, but each goroutine has its own stack. The Go runtime manages the allocation and deallocation of goroutine stacks efficiently, growing and shrinking them as needed.
7. **Concurrency Safety**: Go's design and language features, such as goroutine scheduling, channels, and memory safety, help prevent common concurrency issues like race conditions and deadlocks.

Goroutines are lightweight and efficient, allowing Go programs to handle thousands or even millions of concurrent tasks with minimal overhead. This concurrency model, combined with channels for communication and synchronization, makes Go well-suited for building scalable and efficient concurrent systems.",how do goroutines work?,[],general coding,,,1,,1,false,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
